---
description: MCP tool usage rules — when and how to use Context7 and sequential thinking
alwaysApply: true
---

## CONTEXT7 — USE AUTOMATICALLY
Use Context7 MCP without being asked for ANY of the following:
- Library or framework documentation (React, Hono, Next.js, Astro, Drizzle, Clerk, Stripe, etc.)
- API reference for any external service
- Package setup or configuration steps
- CLI tool usage and flags
- Version-specific syntax or behavior

Never rely on training data for library documentation — it may be outdated.
Always fetch current docs via Context7 before generating code that uses a library.

## GITHUB MCP — USE AUTOMATICALLY
Use GitHub MCP without being asked for ANY of the following:
- Searching code patterns across repos
- Reading PR diffs or commit history for context
- Creating or updating issues from bugs found during development
- Checking if a similar implementation already exists in the codebase

## PLAYWRIGHT MCP — USE AUTOMATICALLY
Use Playwright MCP without being asked for ANY of the following:
- Verifying a UI flow works after implementing it
- Testing auth flows (login, logout, signup)
- Checking responsive layouts after CSS changes
- Verifying Stripe checkout flow in development
- Any task where "does this look/work correctly" needs a visual answer

## SEQUENTIAL THINKING — USE FOR COMPLEX REASONING
Use the sequential-thinking MCP tool when:
- The task involves multiple interdependent decisions
- Architecture or system design questions with tradeoffs
- Debugging a non-obvious issue with multiple possible causes
- Planning a feature that touches more than 3 files or systems

Do NOT use sequential thinking for:
- Simple, self-contained code generation
- Straightforward bug fixes with an obvious cause
- Tasks where a structured review workflow is already defined for the session
